  "prompt": "What will happen if I take Prozac 20 mg daily?",
  "response": "Prozac (fluoxetine) is a selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI) commonly prescribed to treat conditions such as **depression**, **anxiety disorders**, **obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD)**, **panic disorder**, and **bulimia nervosa**. If you take **20 mg daily**, here\u2019s what you might expect:\n\n### **Intended Effects**\n1. **Improved Mood**: Over time (typically 4\u20136 weeks), Prozac may help alleviate symptoms of depression and anxiety by increasing serotonin levels in the brain.\n2. **Reduced Anxiety**: It can help manage excessive worry, panic attacks, or obsessive thoughts.\n3. **Better Sleep and Energy**: Some people experience improved sleep and increased energy as their mood stabilizes.\n\n### **Side Effects**\nWhile many people tolerate Prozac well, some may experience side effects, especially when starting the medication. Common side effects include:\n- **Nausea** or upset stomach\n- **Headache**\n- **Insomnia** or drowsiness\n- **Dry mouth**\n- **Sweating**\n- **Decreased appetite** or weight changes\n- **Sexual dysfunction** (e.g., reduced libido, difficulty achieving orgasm)\n\nThese side effects often diminish as your body adjusts to the medication.\n\n### **Important Considerations**\n1. **Time Frame**: It may take several weeks for the full therapeutic effects to be noticeable. Be patient and consistent with your dosage.\n2. **Gradual Adjustment**: If you\u2019re just starting Prozac, your doctor may begin with a lower dose (e.g., 10 mg) and gradually increase it to 20 mg to minimize side effects.\n3. **Avoid Stopping Suddenly**: Stopping Prozac abruptly can cause withdrawal symptoms like dizziness, mood swings, or \"brain zaps.\" Always consult your doctor before discontinuing.\n4. **Interactions**: Prozac can interact with other medications or supplements, so inform your doctor about all substances you\u2019re taking.\n5. **Monitoring**: Your doctor may monitor your progress and adjust the dosage as needed.\n\n### **Rare but Serious Risks**\n- **Increased Suicide Risk**: In some individuals, especially those under 25, Prozac may initially increase suicidal thoughts. Contact your doctor immediately if you experience worsening depression or suicidal ideation.\n- **Serotonin Syndrome**: A rare but serious condition caused by excessive serotonin levels, often due to interactions with other serotonin-boosting drugs. Symptoms include agitation, rapid heart rate, and high fever.\n- **Mania or Hypomania**: In people with bipolar disorder, Prozac may trigger manic episodes.\n\n### **What to Do**\n- Take Prozac exactly as prescribed by your doctor.\n- Keep track of your symptoms and side effects, and report them to your doctor.\n- Attend follow-up appointments to ensure the medication is working effectively.\n\nIf you have concerns or experience severe side effects, consult your healthcare provider immediately. Never adjust your dosage or stop taking Prozac without professional guidance.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
